author: @fynaglin9075
text:
Here's the thing. As soon as it was revealed Clarence's wife Ginny was in attendance at the Jan 6th rally (which kicked off the insurrection) he could have said, "Okay I'm out..." and quietly retired. No one would have known anything more than that. Obviously he didn't, and on top of this (as of this posting) it came to light Clarence has been receiving residual income from properties under a company which is no longer in existence since 2006. This may or may not be connected to his sugar-daddy selling/buying from him property around his home as well. While a lawyer could argue those yacht-vacations may not qualify as "gifts", the income from the now-extinct property company can easily be argued as illegal. My question though is "Why?" Why didn't Clarence step down after Jan 6th? Knowing what he knew and what could be argued as illegal? Why didn't he take the easy ticket and retire, leaving the media to focus on other GOP donors/lobbyists/politicians? There's only one plausible reason I can think of. He believes the GOP will have his back. 

He sits on the Court, with all his dirty laundry being aired, seemingly confident he is untouchable. Judicial impeachment requires a simple House majority (which won't happen) and a 2/3 majority of the Senate (which DEFINITELY won't happen). But there's always a chance, using lesser-known bylaws which are generally called "nuclear options". Such an option had been used previously dealing with both SCOTUS and the Senate in regards to recesses and Recess Appointments, and that aided in allowing the GOP to pack SCOTUS just before Trump's term was up. It also helped the GOP in essentially blocking SCOTUS appointments under Obama (something Mitch McConnell has professed on camera to being "one of the greatest accomplishments of his political career"). There are many others lying around in Congress, we never hear them because both parties are very reluctant to use them now for fear it sets a precedent to which the other party can abuse in the future.

Why bring that up ? To provide a presently-unseen way to prevent Clarence from being as untouchable as he may believe, even if the GOP has his back. The problem lies in IF and WHEN such a nuclear option is found AND used. If someone manages to find such a way and uses it to either impeach or indict Clarence for all this, do you really think the GOP will defend him? My guess would be, "absolutely not." If such a future scenario plays out where somehow Clarence can be held to account for all of this, under the law, do you really think all the old, rich, white men of the GOP will come to his aid? I think they would collectively lean in and whisper, "We thank you for your service..." and quietly let Clarence sink. Very likely having another SCOTUS appointment or two ready to go to fill his soon-to-be-vacant seat.
